**Sec. 80001 – Exemption of Certain Assets**  
The Higher Education Act of 1965 is amended to exclude from the Expected Family Contribution calculation the net value of a family’s primary residence farm, a small business with ≤100 employees owned by the family, and commercial fishing assets (vessels, permits). These exemptions apply to financial aid determinations for award years starting July 1, 2026.

**Sec. 81001 – Loan Limits for Graduate/Professional Students and Parent Borrowers**  
Graduate and professional students lose eligibility for Direct PLUS loans after July 1, 2026, and for subsidized Direct Stafford loans after July 1, 2012. Annual Direct Unsubsidized Stafford limits rise to $20,500 for graduate students and $50,000 for professional students starting July 1, 2026, with aggregate caps of $100,000 for non-professional graduates and $200,000 for professionals (minus prior borrowing). Parent PLUS annual limits drop to $20,000 and aggregate limits to $65,000 per dependent student, effective July 1, 2026. A lifetime borrowing cap of $257,500 (excluding PLUS loans to dependents) is established.

**Sec. 82001 – Loan Repayment**  
By July 1, 2028, borrowers with pre-2026 income-contingent loans must switch to either the Repayment Assistance Plan or income-based repayment. New loans originated on or after July 1, 2026, are restricted to standard repayment (10–25 years based on balance) or the Repayment Assistance Plan. Excepted loans (e.g., PLUS loans to dependents) must use standard repayment only. Income-contingent repayment is repealed effective July 1, 2028.

**Sec. 82002 – Deferment; Forbearance**  
Unemployment and economic hardship deferments are eliminated for loans originated on or after July 1, 2027. Forbearance is capped at 9 months within any 24-month period for such loans.

**Sec. 82003 – Loan Rehabilitation**  
The number of times a borrower may rehabilitate defaulted FFEL, Direct, or Perkins loans increases from one to two, effective July 1, 2027. Minimum monthly payments for Direct loans originated on or after July 1, 2027, are set at $10.

**Sec. 82004 – Public Service Loan Forgiveness**  
On-time payments under the Repayment Assistance Plan are added to the list of qualifying payments for Public Service Loan Forgiveness.

**Sec. 82005 – Student Loan Servicing**  
$1 billion is appropriated for Direct Loan Program servicing costs, available until expended.

**Sec. 83001 – Eligibility**  
For Pell Grant calculations starting July 1, 2026, foreign income of parents (for dependent students) and students (for independent students) is included in adjusted gross income. Students with a Student Aid Index ≥2× the maximum Pell Grant become ineligible, effective July 1, 2026.

**Sec. 83002 – Workforce Pell Grants**  
A new Workforce Pell Grant program launches July 1, 2026, providing prorated Pell Grants to students in short-term (8–15 weeks), non-degree workforce programs (150–600 clock hours) that meet state and federal criteria (e.g., high-skill alignment, job placement ≥70%). Students cannot hold graduate credentials or be enrolled in such programs concurrently with other Pell Grants.

**Sec. 83003 – Pell Shortfall**  
The Pell Grant shortfall reserve is increased from $2.17 billion to $12.67 billion.

**Sec. 83004 – Federal Pell Grant Exclusion**  
Effective July 1, 2026, students receiving non-Federal grants (state, institutional, or private) equal to or exceeding their cost of attendance become ineligible for Federal Pell Grants.

**Sec. 84001 – Ineligibility Based on Low Earning Outcomes**  
Institutions lose eligibility for federal student aid for programs where graduates’ median earnings (adjusted for inflation) fall below the median earnings of working adults (ages 25–34, high school diploma or bachelor’s degree) for 2 of 3 years. Small programs (<30 graduates) may aggregate data. Institutions can appeal and regain eligibility after 2 years of ineligibility.

**Sec. 85001 – Delay of Borrower Defense Rule**  
Borrower defense regulations published November 1, 2022, are delayed until July 1, 2035, for loans originated before that date. Pre-2020 borrower defense rules are revived.

**Sec. 85002 – Delay of Closed School Discharge Rule**  
Closed school discharge regulations added in 2022 are delayed until July 1, 2035, for loans originated before that date. Pre-2022 rules are restored.

**Sec. 86001 – Garden of Heroes**  
$40 million is appropriated to the National Endowment for the Humanities (2025–2028) for statues commemorating American heroes under Executive Orders 13934, 13978, and 14189.

**Sec. 87001 – Potential Sponsor Vetting for Unaccompanied Alien Children**  
$300 million is appropriated to the Office of Refugee Resettlement (2025–2028) for background checks, home studies, gang marking exams, data sharing to prevent child labor/trafficking, and coordination with state child welfare agencies for unaccompanied alien children. [end of text]


